<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-459-984  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 459 984.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  May 2 1990 n1506 p16(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Soviets look West for chip aid.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Farish, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Soviet Union, which has been largely unsuccessful in itsattempts to clone US semiconductor technology, could prove to be amassive market for Western microprocessors once export laws arerelaxed by the Coordinating Committee on Export Controls (CoCom).andO;The Soviets have obtained legitimate chips in Pacific Rimcountries not bound by CoCom, but have manufactured copies becauseof the prohibitive costs of chips obtained in this manner.andO;Results have been second-rate, and the Soviets are expected to beeager to obtain the real thing.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Soviet UnionMicroprocessorsSemiconductorsMarket AnalysisDemandTechnology TransferCoordinating Committee for Multilateral Export ControlsReverse Engineering.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>